    <item>
      <title>California AB 587 vs. New York S895: What's Different and Why It Matters</title>
      <link>https://krmaynard.github.io/blog/ab587-vs-s895.html</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://krmaynard.github.io/blog/ab587-vs-s895.html</guid>
      <pubDate>Sun, 05 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description><![CDATA[Both laws require social media transparency reports on content moderation. AB 587 focuses on policy disclosure — what the terms of service say and aggregate enforcement figures. S895 requires structured operational data: counts of actions taken, by category, every quarter. The overlap is enough to share review cycles; the data requirements are different enough to force separate pipelines.]]></description>
    </item>

    <item>
      <title>Roblox's California and New York Transparency Reports Are Live</title>
      <link>https://krmaynard.github.io/blog/roblox-ca-ny-reports.html</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://krmaynard.github.io/blog/roblox-ca-ny-reports.html</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 01 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description><![CDATA[Roblox's California AB 587 (H2 2025) and New York S895 (Q4 2025) state social media transparency reports are now filed. Running both in parallel — separate data tracks, shared cross-functional review capacity across Legal, Policy, and Engineering — was a useful forcing function for building more durable reporting infrastructure.]]></description>
    </item>

    <item>
      <title>What EU DSA Transparency Reporting Actually Requires</title>
      <link>https://krmaynard.github.io/blog/dsa-transparency-requirements.html</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://krmaynard.github.io/blog/dsa-transparency-requirements.html</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description><![CDATA[Article 15 applies to all intermediary services: annual reports covering authority orders, notices, own-initiative moderation, and automated tool use. Article 42 adds substantially more for VLOPs: bi-annual reporting, category and language breakdowns, decision timeline data, appeals figures, government order details. The practical gap is significant — VLOP obligations require purpose-built reporting systems, not ad-hoc exports.]]></description>
    </item>

